latestPosts.caption:
This year at the Met gala, I accessorized my look with a robotic spine. 
This piece was made painstakingly—if not, obsessively—by Timothy @timothyaboll and Lisa @lisa_jiang_ , who took my vision and ran with it until it became something far more intricate, far more intimate than I ever imagined. A gear driven structure built into a custom corset, the spine was engineered to flex and move with me. But its true function wasn’t  mechanical—it was metaphysical. 
Let me explain how: very few people know this, but Alexander McQueen changed my life. 
I was 30 when I wandered into Savage Beauty exhibition at the Met—and what I found there wasn’t just fashion. It was a revelation. I left that exhibit electrified, knowing that I could never look at fashion the same way again, and more importantly, I couldn’t look at myself the same way either. 
That day, I stopped waiting for permission and started acting on instinct. This spine was an homage to McQueen’s spinal corset (Spring/Summer ‘98).
To me, wearing that robotic spine wasn’t just tied to my robotic dog Vector but it was my secret homage to McQueen and also myself—acknowledging what holds me up. To celebrate the scaffolding that I built in secret. To walk into a room not as a finished product, but as a living machine—still adapting, still evolving. It represents my transformation—vertebra by vertebra, choice by choice. 
Yes, I’ve always had a thing for tailoring. I spent years equating menswear with power, with control, with armor. But that day at Savage Beauty, something shifted. I saw that strength didn’t have to mean subtraction. That softness and structure could coexist. That adornment could be resistance, if not my entire existence. That becoming yourself—truly—is the most daring thing of all.
And so this year, I wore a robotic spine. Not just as fashion, but as memory, as meaning, as a tribute to the girl who wandered into the museum—and walked out determined to rebuild her fashion world.

Arriving to the Met, back home and everything in between but the last 2 slides say it all!

It’s already been a week and I can’t thank my team enough for all their hard work, patience and dedication. Thank you to each and everyone in helping me bring my vision to life, it truly was a collective genius! Hope you all are rested well until we meet again😉
And a special shout out to @radik_aijarikov and @ahmad.alek without them none of this would be possible!

latestPosts.caption:
This year at the Met Gala, accessories were crowned by many as the real MVPs —but the true MVPs are actually the visionaries and craftspeople who make these impossible ideas a reality. What looks like magic on the carpet is, in truth, the result of countless hours (if not months) of collaboration, experimentation, and relentless dedication.

I partnered with Miodrag Gubernic, a creative force whose work has shaped some of the most iconic sci-fi moments on film. Together, we set out to reimagine what accessories could be—fusing traditional artistry with futuristic developments like 3D printing.

The hat was a sculptural feat—painstakingly prototyped, reprinted, and reworked until it felt both weightless and monumental. With so many pivots, we accomplished the final look in a matter of days—what could have easily taken months. Watching Vector Mini evolve from digital sketches into a bag matching the fully operational Vector robot dog was surreal. Every servo, every joint, every movement was engineered.
#metgala

Robotic Spine by @timothyaboll and @lisa_jiang_ for @hautemona for her 2025 Met Gala look.

Huge thank you to Mona for trusting us with your vision, it was a dream come true to work on this project together.

latestPosts.caption:
Huge thank you to @harpersbazaarserbia for letting me share the full story behind my 2025 Met Gala look.

This wasn’t just a fashion moment - it was a celebration of collective genius: from Thom Browne’s visionary team to master artisans in India and the brilliant engineers at MIT who brought Vector the robot dog to life. Together, we fused heritage, tech, and craftsmanship into something truly unforgettable. So excited to pull back the curtain on the creativity (and a little chaos!) that made it happen.  I couldn’t have done this without my incredible team and masterminds @alikhan_photography @radik_aijarikov
